ist audience in mind. It will have a particular value for those requiring introductions to aspects of the Gaelic language. It will also be of great interest to those who are embarking on research on Gaelic for the first time. Authors include Colm O Baoill, David Adger, Rob Dunbar, Seosamh Watson, Ken Nilsen, Ken MacKinnon and Ronald Black.This book:*Deals with a wide range of aspects of Gaelic*Places the study of the Gaelic language within the context of modern linguistic research*Encourages and supports further study*Includes chapters by a number of leading experts on Gaelic language  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aLanguage and languages. 0aScottish Gaelic language. 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aAdger, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBosch, Anna R. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreeze, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunbar, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKinnon, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacleod, Michelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMacleod, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcEwan-Fujita, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNilsen, Kenneth E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson, Moray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson, Seosamh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aÓ Baoill, Colm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g